data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone too. The fix is cooperative cancellation with `CancellationToken`.

## Why it breaks

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's work doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't magically stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. `Task.WaitAsync` lets the **caller** stop waiting, but `work()` keeps running on the thread pool until it finishes. If `work` is a long loop, pass the token in and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using`/dispose it. A `CTS` with a timeout allocates an internal timer — leaking it leaks the timer. |
| **Catching too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from an unrelated cancellation propagated by `work`. |
| **Blocking the thread pool** | `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` blocks a thread. If this is called from ASP.NET Core, prefer an `async` signature returning `Task<T>` with `await` instead. |

## If `work` must actually stop (not just be abandoned)

Accept and forward a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then inside `work`, check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## If work is truly uncooperative (e.g., third-party code)

Move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
